stix:STIX_Header.stix:Title: HSBC E-Advice Themed Phishing Email Contains Malicious Attachment
stix:STIX_Header.stix:Description:
On 29 July 2013, A HSBC E-Advice themed phishing email was observed. The emails contained a .zip attachment that was found to contain a variant of the Zeus Trojan. The malicious executable has the capability to harvest user credentials, send data to a remote Command and Control (C2) as well as download and execute files. Analysis also revealed eight unique call back domains and IP addresses.
This document incorporates data originally released as MIFR-321693.

Packer: AHTeam EP Protector 0.3 (fake PCGuard 4.03-4.15) -> FEUERRADER Compile Date: 2013-06-16 11:22:34 UTC
This file was found to be a variant of the Zeus Trojan. Upon execution, the malware writes a unique identifier to the system registry in the format {%08X-%04X-%04X-%02X%02X-%02X%02X%02X%02X%02X%02X}. For example: HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\WinRAR HWID = {5CF46854-5EFD-4696-8892-B749151810BE}
In an attempt to harvest login information, the malware provides parsing functionality for a number of third-party software applications, with a particular focus on FTP software.
The malware has the capability to send data to a remote C2 system via the HTTP POST method and download and execute files from a remote system. If a Portable Executable (PE) is downloaded, the file will be saved to the user's %TEMP% directory and executed.
Analysis revealed 8 call back domains and IP addresses.
